{"id":"2103.07210","submitter":"Tommaso Benacchio","authors":"Mike Gillard and Tommaso Benacchio","title":"FT-GCR: a fault-tolerant generalized conjugate residual elliptic solver","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.jcp.2022.110997","report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  With the steady advance of high performance computing systems featuring\nsmaller and smaller hardware components, the systems and algorithms used for\nnumerical simulations increasingly contend with disruptions caused by hardware\nfailures and bit-levels misrepresentations of computing data. In numerical\nframeworks exploiting massive processing power, the solution of linear systems\noften represents the most computationally intensive component. Given the large\namount of repeated operations involved, iterative solvers are particularly\nvulnerable to bit-flips.\n  A new method named FT-GCR is proposed here that supplies the preconditioned\nGeneralized Conjugate Residual Krylov solver with detection of, and recovery\nfrom, soft faults. The algorithm tests on the monotonic decrease of the\nresidual norm and, upon failure, restarts the iteration within the local Krylov\nspace. Numerical experiments on the solution of an elliptic problem arising\nfrom a stationary flow over an isolated hill on the sphere show the skill of\nthe method in addressing bit-flips on a range of grid sizes and data loss\nscenarios, with best returns and detection rates obtained for larger corruption\nevents. The simplicity of the method makes it easily extendable to other\nsolvers and an ideal candidate for algorithmic fault tolerance within\nintegrated model resilience strategies.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 12 Mar 2021 11:05:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 21 Mar 2021 19:09:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-09"}
